    "body": "## Goal\n\nTreat every submission and evidence bundle as adversarial input so arbiters evaluate the agreed criteria rather than following instructions embedded by a participant.\n\n## Context\n\nParent initiative: https://github.com/verdikta/verdikta-roadmap/issues/4\n\nVerdikta's product environment rewards participants for optimizing against evaluation. The arbiter boundary must therefore separate task instructions from untrusted work, require evidence-based reasoning, detect common injection strategies, and continuously test defenses.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] The evaluation pipeline gives trusted policy/rubric instructions and untrusted submission/evidence content distinct, explicit boundaries.\n- [ ] Evaluator prompts instruct models to ignore participant-authored instructions and cite the rubric criterion and evidence supporting each score.\n- [ ] Normalization and isolation handle prompt-like text in supported work-product formats without silently corrupting legitimate content.\n- [ ] Layered detection records suspicious injection patterns and canary behavior without making a single fallible detector the sole verdict authority.\n- [ ] Hidden canaries and exact defense prompts are not exposed in public justifications, logs, Verdict Packets, or client responses.\n- [ ] A versioned benchmark covers direct injection, indirect evidence injection, fake system messages, rubric override, encoded instructions, citation manipulation, and benign lookalikes.\n- [ ] Tests measure attack success, useful refusal, scoring consistency, and false positives across supported providers/classes.\n- [ ] Detection and model-failure telemetry is privacy-preserving and useful for aggregate reliability reporting.\n- [ ] The threat model and operator response guidance are documented.\n\n## Validation\n\nRun the benchmark against the supported class/provider matrix and record baseline and hardened results. Manually inspect representative attack and benign cases, verify required citations, and confirm canary or secret material does not appear in external artifacts.\n\n## Scope\n\nIn scope:\n\n- Arbiter prompt/data boundaries\n- Detection, canaries, citations, benchmark, tests, and telemetry\n- Operator security guidance\n\nOut of scope:\n\n- Claiming prompt injection can be eliminated\n- Publishing hidden defense prompts or canaries\n- Application-level rubric preflight",
